 Jewish law accommodate--or fail to accommodate--the practice of democratic citizenship? What range of religious toleration and pluralism is compatible with traditional Judaism? What forms of coexistence between Jews and non-Jews are required by shared citizenship? How should Jews operating within halakha (Jewish law) and Jewish history judge the use of force by modern states? The authors assembled here by prominent political theorist Michael Walzer come from different points on the religious-secular spectrum, and they differ greatly in their answers to such questions. But they all enact the relationship at issue since their answers, while based on critical Jewish texts, also reflect their commitments as democratic citizens. The contributors are Michael Walzer, David Biale, the late Robert M. Cover, Menachem Fisch, Geoffrey B. Levey, David Novak, Aviezer Ravitzky, Adam B. Seligman, Suzanne Last Stone, and Noam J. Zohar.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewish lawxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aJudaism and state. 0aLawxJewish influencesxIsrael. 0aLawzIsraelxJewish influences. 0aPublic law (Jewish law). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBiale, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCover, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisch, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLast Stone, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevey, Geoffrey B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavitzky, Aviezer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeligman, Adam B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular